'''John Adams''' (c. 1746 – 1817)  was a British politician who sat in the [[House of Commons]] between  1774 and 1780.

Adams was the son of John Adams of [[Whitland]], Carmarthenshire who was [[High Sheriff of Pembrokeshire]] in 1758. His mother was Elizabeth Lloyd, daughter of [[Walter Lloyd (1678-1747)|Walter Lloyd]], M.P  of Peterwell and sister of [[Sir Herbert Lloyd, 1st Baronet]]. He matriculated at [[Queen’s College, Oxford]] on 23 January 1766, aged 19 and was created MA at Oxford in 1773.<ref name = ALUM>{{cite web| url =  https://archive.org/stream/alumnioxonienses01univuoft#page/6/mode/2up| title=Alumni oxonienses: the members of the University of Oxford, 1715-1886| author= Foster, Joseph |publisher= University of Oxford| accessdate = 20 August 2017}}</ref>  It also appears that entered [[Lincoln’s Inn]] in 1765 and was called to the bar in 1772.<ref name = HOP>{{cite web| url = http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1754-1790/member/adams-john-1746-1817 | title= ADAMS, John (?1746-1817), of Peterwell, Card | publisher= History of Parliament Online| accessdate = 20 August 2017}}</ref> In 1769 he inherited the Peterwell and [[Falcondale]] estates from his uncle Sir Herbert Lloyd, Bt who is said to have shot himself on account of his large debts. The estate was therefore already heavily mortgaged, and Adams amassed more debts and attempted to sell the estate.<ref name=ANW>{{cite web|url=http://anws.llgc.org.uk/cgi-bin/anw/fulldesc_nofr?inst_id=1&coll_id=20253&expand=|title=Archives Network Wales - Peterwell and Falcondale Estate Records|website=anws.llgc.org.uk|accessdate=26 August 2017}}</ref> His father died before 1772.<ref name="nationalarchives">{{cite web|url=http://discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk/details/r/D446965|title=Will of John Adams of Whitland , Carmarthenshire|website=The National Archives|accessdate=26 August 2017}}</ref>
In 1776, a London attorney, who held the original mortgage, bought the Peterwell estate.<ref name = ANW/>

Adams was appointed [[High Sheriff of Carmarthenshire]] in 1774.<ref name="thegazette">{{cite web|url=https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/11429/page/1/data.pdf|date=8 February 1774|title=The London Gazette|accessdate=26 August 2017}}</ref>   In [[British general election, 1774|1774]] he was returned as [[Member of Parliament]] for both [[Carmarthen (UK Parliament constituency)|Carmarthen]] and [[Wendover (UK Parliament constituency)|Wendover]] and decided to take his seat at Carmarthen. He had gained Carmarthen through the interest of [[Griffith Philipps]] but  Philipps dropped him as candidate for Carmarthen in 1780. He considered standing at Cardigan, where his remaining estate gave him an interest, but decided not to enter the poll.<ref name = HOP/>

Long before his death Lloyd had spent his inheritance. He died on 2 June 1817.<ref name = HOP/>

