{{short description| Ship sunk in Lake Huron in 1913 }} {|{{Infobox ship begin}} {{Infobox ship image |Ship image=File:Charles S Price before 1913 Great Lakes storm.png |Ship caption= }} {{Infobox ship career |Hide header= |Ship country= |Ship flag= |Ship name=SS ''Charles S. Price'' |Ship operator= |Ship ordered= |Ship builder=[[American Ship Building Company]], [[Lorain, Ohio|Lorain]],&nbsp;[[Ohio]] |Ship yard number=381 |Ship laid down= |Ship launched=1910 |Ship completed= |Ship acquired= |Ship in service= |Ship out of service= |Ship fate=Sunk, 9 November 1913 |Ship status= |Ship notes= }} {{Infobox ship characteristics |Hide header= |Header caption= |Ship class= |Ship tonnage=6322 (gross), 4901 (net) |Ship displacement= |Ship length={{convert|524|ft|m|abbr=on}} |Ship beam={{convert|54|ft|m|abbr=on}} |Ship height={{convert|30|ft|m|abbr=on}} |Ship draught= |Ship draft= |Ship ice class= |Ship sail plan= |Ship propulsion= |Ship speed= |Ship capacity= |Ship crew=28 |Ship notes= }} |} [[File:SS Charles S. Price.jpg|left|thumb|Bow of the SS ''Charles S. Price'' before sinking into Lake Huron.]] The '''SS ''Charles S. Price''''' was a steel hulled ship lost on [[Lake Huron]] on November 9, 1913 during the [[Great Lakes storm of 1913]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://images.maritimehistoryofthegreatlakes.ca/55997/data?n=1 |title=Maritime History of the Great Lakes |accessdate=2017-02-12}}</ref>
The ''Price'' was found on 10 November 1913 with her bow above water, and her stern dipping below. Because of her disposition, the ship's length could not be measured to make a positive identification of the vessel: the wreck was initially assumed to be the ''[[SS Regina (1907)|Regina]]''. The vessel was eventually identified as the ''Price'' before she sank on 17 November.
The salvage rights to the ''Price'' were sold to the Great Lakes Towing and Wrecking company. In the summer of 1916, salvage of the ''Price'' was attempted. Divers cut a hole in the side of the aft hull. The hole allowed divers to enter the wreck. They attempted to seal breaks in the hull and built bulkheads so that the wreck could be floated. However, salvaging the wreck was eventually considered too costly to be worth the expense and the Great Lakes Towing and Wrecking company abandoned attempts to raise her.
Salvage rights were eventually sold to the American Salvage Co., but they too were unable to salvage the wreck.
