{{other ships|USS Conestoga}} {|{{Infobox ship begin|infobox caption=yes}} {{Infobox ship image |Ship image=USS Conestoga (AT-54) at San Diego c1921.jpg{{!}}border |Ship caption=''Conestoga'' in 1921 }} {{Infobox ship career |Hide header= |Ship country=United States of America |Ship flag= {{USN flag|1921}} |Ship name=USS ''Conestoga'' |Ship namesake= |Ship ordered= |Ship builder=[[Bethlehem Sparrows Point Shipyard|Maryland Steel Company]], [[Sparrows Point, Maryland]], U.S. |Ship laid down=1904 |Ship launched= |Ship acquired=by purchase, 14 September 1917 |Ship commissioned=10 November 1917 |Ship decommissioned= |Ship in service= |Ship out of service= |Ship struck= |Ship renamed= |Ship reclassified=AT-54, 17 July 1920 |Ship homeport= |Ship motto= |Ship nickname= |Ship honors= |Ship fate=Declared lost with all her crew, 30 June 1921 [wreck found 2016] |Ship status= |Ship notes= }} {{Infobox ship characteristics |Hide header= |Header caption= |Ship type=[[Tugboat]] |Ship displacement={{convert|420|LT|t|abbr=on}} |Ship length={{convert|170|ft|m|abbr=on}} |Ship beam={{convert|29|ft|m|abbr=on}} |Ship draft={{convert|15|ft|m|abbr=on}} |Ship propulsion= |Ship speed={{convert|13|kn|mph km/h|lk=in|abbr=on}} |Ship range= |Ship complement=56 |Ship armament=1 × {{convert|3|in|mm|abbr=on}} gun |Ship armor= |Ship notes= }} |}
The second '''USS ''Conestoga'' (SP-1128/AT-54)''' was an ocean-going [[tug]] in the [[United States Navy]]. Commissioned in 1917, it disappeared in the Pacific Ocean in 1921. The fate of the vessel was a mystery until its wreck was positively identified in 2016.
== Construction == The tug was built for the [[Reading Company#Philadelphia and Reading Railway: 1896–1923|Philadelphia and Reading Railway]] as the ''Conestoga'' in 1904 by [[Maryland Steel Company]], [[Sparrows Point, Maryland]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Bethlehem Steel Company, Sparrows Point MD|url=http://www.shipbuildinghistory.com/history/shipyards/2large/inactive/bethsparrowspoint.htm|website=Shipbuilding History|publisher=Tim Colton|accessdate=24 March 2016|location=Delray Beach, FL|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303191419/http://www.shipbuildinghistory.com/history/shipyards/2large/inactive/bethsparrowspoint.htm|archivedate=3 March 2016|df=}}</ref> She was purchased on 14 September 1917 for the [[World War I]] duty and designated '''SP-1128'''. She was commissioned on 10 November 1917, Lieutenant (junior grade) C. Olsen, USNRF, in command.
==Service history== [[File:USS Conestoga's ship's company, 1921.png|left|thumb|''Conestoga''{{'}}s crew in 1921.]] Assigned to the [[Submarines in the United States Navy|Submarine Force]], ''Conestoga'' carried out towing duties along the Atlantic coast, transported supplies and guns, escorted convoys to [[Bermuda]] and the [[Azores]], and cruised with the American Patrol Detachment in the vicinity of the Azores. At the end of the war she was attached to Naval Base No. 13, Azores, from which she towed disabled ships and escorted convoys until her arrival at [[New York City|New York]] on 26 September 1919. She was then assigned to harbor tug duty in the 5th Naval District at [[Norfolk, Virginia]].
''Conestoga'' (which had received the hull number '''AT-54''' in July 1920) went to the Pacific in late 1920. She was at [[San Diego, California]] and [[Mare Island, California]], during the first three months of 1921. On 25 March of that year the tug steamed out of Mare Island, with a barge of coal sailing via Pearl Harbor to take up an assignment as station ship at [[Tutuila]], [[American Samoa]].<ref name="smithsonian">{{cite web |url=http://www.smithsonianmag.com/history/discovery-uss-conestoga-researchers-have-solved-naval-mystery-was-nearly-100-years-old-180958538/ |title=With the Discovery of the USS Conestoga, Researchers Have Solved a Mystery That Was Nearly 100 Years Old |website=[[Smithsonian (magazine)|Smithsonian]] |publisher=[[Smithsonian Institution]] |date=March 23, 2016 |first=Suzy |last=Khimm |accessdate=April 3, 2016}}</ref>
Commanded by Lt. Ernest Larkin Jones, ''Conestoga'' was not heard from again. Despite an extensive search, the only trace found of her at the time of her loss was a lifeboat bearing the initial letter of her name found near [[Manzanillo, Colima|Manzanillo]], [[Mexico]].<ref name="smithsonian" />
==Rediscovery== [[File:Conestoga-stern-001 noaa-teledyne-seabotix.jpg|thumb|left|Stern view of the shipwreck, colonized with sea anemones.]]
Her wreck was discovered in 2009, as an unidentified shipwreck in the [[Greater Farallones National Marine Sanctuary]], a few miles from Southeast Farallon Island, just off the [[San Francisco]], [[California]] coast. In October 2015, a joint [[NOAA]] and Navy mission confirmed the wreck was the ''Conestoga'' and on 23 March 2016, 95 years after the ship was lost, a formal announcement was made.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Barakat|first1=Matthew|title=Navy tugboat lost for a century found off California coast|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/e2a0eb393f7d43bebd97731e961f1e7a|accessdate=23 March 2016|agency=Associated Press|date=23 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/after-95-years-a-navy-ship-lost-at-sea-with-all-hands-is-finally-discovered/2016/03/22/ebe2e29c-eba7-11e5-b0fd-073d5930a7b7_story.html?tid=pm_local_pop_b|title=After 95 years, a Navy ship lost at sea with all hands is finally discovered|author=Michael E. Ruane|date=23 March 2016|work=Washington Post|accessdate=23 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/03/23/us/uss-conestoga-shipwreck-found-95-years-later/index.html|title=95 years after disappearance, the USS Conestoga is found|first=Mariano|last=Castillo|date=23 March 2016|work=Cable News Network}}</ref> The shipwreck was listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in 2016.
