{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2017}} {{Use British English|date=April 2016}} {{Infobox football biography | name = William Baker | image = | caption = | fullname = William James Baker<ref name="CWGC" /> | birth_date =1882<ref>''England & Wales, Civil Registration Birth Index, 1837-1915''</ref> | birth_place = [[Plymouth]], England | death_date = {{death date and given age|1916|10|22|33|df=y}}<ref name="CWGC" /> | death_place = [[Serre-lès-Puisieux]], France | height = | position = [[Wing half]] | youthyears1 = | youthclubs1 = | years1 = | clubs1 = [[Green Waves F.C.|Green Waves]] | caps1 = | goals1 = | years2 = | clubs2 = De Beers | caps2 = | goals2 = | years3 = {{0|0000}}–1909 | clubs3 = [[Green Waves F.C.|Green Waves]] | caps3 = | goals3 = | years4 = 1909–1915 | clubs4 = [[Plymouth Argyle F.C.|Plymouth Argyle]] | caps4 = 193 | goals4 = 1 }} '''William James Baker''' [[Military Medal|MM]] (1882 – 22 October 1916) was an English professional [[association football|football]] [[wing half]] who played 202 games in the [[Southern Football League|Southern League]] and [[FA Cup]] for [[Plymouth Argyle F.C.|Plymouth Argyle]] between 1909 and 1915.<ref name="GoS">{{Cite web |url=http://www.greensonscreen.co.uk/gosdb-players2.asp?pid=29&scp=1,2,3,4,5,6,7 |title=William Baker |publisher=Greens on Screen |access-date=17 August 2010}}</ref> He also played in the [[Soccer in the United States|United States]] and [[Soccer in South Africa|South Africa]].<ref name="GoS" />
== Personal life == Baker was married.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.footballandthefirstworldwar.org/william-baker-service-record/ |title=William James Baker {{!}} Service Record {{!}} Football and the First World War |work=Football and the First World War |access-date=20 November 2017 |language=en-US}}</ref> He served in the [[Football Battalion]] of the [[Middlesex Regiment]] during the [[First World War]] and rose to the rank of [[sergeant]].<ref name="CWGC">{{Cite web |url=https://www.cwgc.org/find-war-dead/casualty/311628/baker,-william-james/ |title=Casualty details |publisher=[[Commonwealth War Graves Commission]] |access-date=10 September 2010}}</ref> He was [[wounded in action]] at [[Battle of Vimy Ridge|Vimy Ridge]] in June 1916 and received the [[Military Medal]].<ref>{{Cite book |title=When the Whistle Blows: The Story of the Footballers' Battalion in the Great War |last=Riddoch |first=Andrew |last2=Kemp |first2=John |last3=Holmes |first3=Richard |date=20 November 2008 |publisher=Haynes Publishing |isbn=9781844256563 |edition=1st |location=Sparkford |pages=105–107 |language=English}}</ref> On 22 October 1916, Baker was killed by [[German Army (German Empire)|German]] [[artillery]] fire near [[Serre-lès-Puisieux]] during the [[Battle of the Somme]] and is commemorated at Sucrerie Military Cemetery at [[Colincamps]].<ref name="CWGC" />{{Sfn|Riddoch|2008|p=155}}
